# GRAFCET Sequence Logic — Multi-Station Packaging Line

## Purpose
GRAFCET (sequential function chart) defines how each station in the
packaging line operates in sequence, with interlocks ensuring one station
doesn't proceed until the prior station's step is confirmed complete —
critical for both correct operation and equipment protection.

## Simplified sequence overview
```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Idle
    Idle --> Station1_Load: Start command + parts present
    Station1_Load --> Station1_Process: Load confirmed
    Station1_Process --> Station2_Transfer: Process complete
    Station2_Transfer --> Station2_Pack: Transfer confirmed
    Station2_Pack --> Station3_Seal: Pack complete
    Station3_Seal --> Idle: Seal complete, cycle done
    Station1_Process --> Fault: Fault detected
    Station2_Pack --> Fault: Fault detected
    Fault --> Idle: Fault cleared + reset
```

## Key interlock principles
- Each station step requires confirmation (sensor feedback) before the next
  step is enabled — prevents equipment collision or double-processing
- A fault at any station halts the sequence and holds state, rather than
  continuing blindly — protects both product and equipment
- Manual reset required after fault clearance, consistent with the
  fault-handling approach used in the automation project's PLC logic

## Why GRAFCET matters for maintenance/installation roles
Even without programming a PLC from scratch, being able to **read** a
GRAFCET or sequence chart is what lets a technician quickly understand where
in a multi-station process a fault occurred, and whether a stoppage is a
mechanical, electrical, or sequencing issue — directly relevant to
troubleshooting "programmable logic controls" on an installed line.
